cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  Even though a repeat of the Delta suit at GAME LEVEL is not strictly forcing, responder should bear in mind that Opener is VERY strong and continue with a near positive (eg: 5-7 points) if possible (by answering as if it WAS a repeat Delta.

If the initial response to Delta agreed the suit (4 steps or more) then a rebid of the suit at game level is obviously "to play".

Any JUMP to GAME in the Delta suit is obviously "to play" and should never be interpreted as a Repeat Delta.

That wouldn't, of course, stop Responder from cue-bidding an undisclosed void if they had a near maximum.

Not sure I'd bother cue-bidding a singleton, though.   Thus 

^c 1@C  -  1@D  -  2@S(Delta)  -  3@C(Q or xx)     -  3@S(Repeat)  -  4@C   shows xx in Spades 

^c 1@C  -  1@D  -  2@H(Delta)  -  3@C(Qx or xxx)  -  3@H(Repeat)  -  3@S   shows a doubleton honour.

A repeat Delta in the same suit ALWAYS sets that suit as trumps.      However 

^c 1@C  -  1@D  -  3@C(Delta)  -  3@S(Hx/xxx)   -  5@C    is always "to play".        Similarly, 

^c 1@C  -  1@D  -  2@H        -      3@D(HH/Hxx)  -  5@H    is simply invitational to 6@H, no more.

Don't forget that after a 4-step or greater response to Delta, or after ANY response to a repeat Delta in the same suit, the suit is agreed as trumps, so a Relay in the next suit up will be the Relay Beta Ask.

We saw examples of that in both of the sequences shown here.|
